Tavuk shish - Turkish chicken kebabs, lavash bread, salad, grilled halloumi and garlic sauce! Perfect combo for a bbq this weekend!

Ingredients:

â€¢2 boneless, skinless chicken breasts (or 4 to 5 boneless, skinless thighs)
â€¢1 medium onion(finely chopped or grated)
â€¢2 cloves garlic(minced)
â€¢1/2 cup plain yogurt (or milk)
3 tablespoons vegetable oil
2 tablespoons tomato paste
1 teaspoon ground black pepper
1 teaspoon paprika
1 teaspoon salt
Optional: red food colouring

Have you ever heard of Oyakodon? ğŸš Oyakodon literally means â€œparent-and-child donburiâ€ and is a delicious Japanese rice bowl dish containing both the chicken ğŸ” and the egg ğŸ¥š. Check out this fun recipe below â¬‡ï¸ï»¿
Ingredients:ï»¿
Â½ ea Chicken breast, cut into small piecesï»¿
Â¼ ea Onion, slicedï»¿
3 ea chicken eggsï»¿
1 tbsp Kappo Shirodashiï»¿
7 floz waterï»¿
1.5 tsp sugarï»¿
1.75 cups cooked riceï»¿
Mitsuba herb, or cilantro as desiredï»¿
Chopped Nori as desiredï»¿
ï»¿
Directions:ï»¿
ï»¿
1. Scramble the eggs in a bowlï»¿
2. Put Kappo Shirodashi and water in a shallow pan, add sugar and bring to a boil. Add chicken and onion. After it comes to a boil then skim off what floats to the top. Simmer for 5-6 min.ï»¿
3. Drizzle in the scrambled eggs and cook for 1 minute with the lid on. Turn off heat when the eggs are half cooked.ï»¿
4. Put the rice into the bowl. Add the cooked egg mixture on top. Garnish with mitsuba or cilantro and chopped nori. Enjoy!ï»¿

#Spicy lamb chops ğŸ˜‹ 

Using a paring knife, cut a few 1/4-inch-deep slashes in each lamb chop. In a large bowl, whisk the yogurt with lemon juice, ginger, garlic, malt vinegar, garam masala, cumin, paprika, cayenne, mace, chilli flakes and 1 teaspoon of salt. Transfer the lamb chops to the marinade and turn to coat, then cover and refrigerate overnight.

Add the oil to the marinade and toss with the lamb chops. Remove the chops from the marinade and let stand at room temperature for 30 minutes.

Light a grill. Season the chops with salt and grill over moderately high heat for 8 minutes, turning once, until well browned. Brush both sides of the chops with the melted butter and grill for another 2 minutes per side for medium-rare.

['For 2 people:
2 chicken breasts
300grs of button mushrooms
1/4 onion
3 cloves of garlic
Parsley
Salt pepper
Olive oil
1 sweet potato
Peel the sweet potato, cut it into thick slices, brush with olive oil, salt and pepper.
Bake on a baking sheet lined with baking paper in the oven at 200 degrees for 25 minutes.
Clean the mushrooms, cut them into pieces and sautÃ© in a spoonful of olive oil until lightly colored.
Brown the 1/4 onion.
Finely mix the mushrooms, onion, garlic and a good pinch of parsley leaves in a food processor.
Using a hammer or a rolling pin, flatten the chicken breasts between 2 sheets of cling film.
Place a good spoonful of mushroom stuffing on each and roll them tightly in cling film.
Steam for 20 minutes.
Put the rest of the stuffing in a small saucepan with 1/2 glass of water and let it simmer.
After 10 minutes add a teaspoon of cornstarch dissolved in a little water and leave to thicken.
Remove the film from the ballotines and make lightly colored in a pan with a drizzle of olive oil.
On a plate, arrange the pieces of sweet potato, 2 good spoons of sauce.
Cut the ballotines in 2 and diagonally and place on the sauce.
Sprinkle with chopped parsley.
Bon appÃ©tit !']

Chicken & mushroom crepes with cheese sauce! 
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
When your fiancÃ¨ asks for mushrooms, you give him mushrooms! 

I made the mix by frying onion and garlic in some butter, then adding chopped mushies, thyme, parsley and spring onion. I pulled apart a roast chicken and diced about 2 cups worth and added to the pan. Then mixed a little flour in vegetable stock and added it to the pan to thicken the mix. I seasoned with salt, pepper and cayenne pepper for a bit of a kick! 

I made the crepes then filled them, rolled them, covered them in a cheese sauce and cooked them in the oven for 10 mins.

The cheese sauce is made from butter, flour, milk, dijon mustard and a little light tasty cheese.

Hi and welcome to our Instagram page! 
Out names are Siobhan and Levi. 
We are just your typical young married couple who love the outdoors, spending time with family and exploring our what our back yard offers ( There is nothing more beautiful then the West Coast of New Zealand!) 
Levi is a dairy farmer and Siobhan is a Rural veterinarian technician who enjoy being in our garden producing our own organic food for ourselves, family and our free range chickens as well as running livestock and cooking hearty meals.

We live on a small property on the West Coast of New Zealand with our 3 cats and 5 free range chickens. 
We battle over 5 metres of rainfall in a year, heavy snow fall during the winter and on going wild wind. 

âœ¨We have a goal of becoming 90% self sufficient by 2022 and keeping all of our produce/livestock (to come) and chickens chemical and pesticide free. 

Please follow along for some awesome things to come! We have a few things in the works that include revamping our current temporary garden bed!

New Place Alert â—
Place : Lajjat - E - Taam 
Location : 255/24, Netaji Subhash Chandra Boss Road, Naktala, Kolkata
This is a newly opened restaurant located near Naktala. Bengalis has a special craving for biriyani and in our kolkata we get different varieties of biriyani. We generally search for biriyani Or the food at a pocket friendly price but some people also search for quality food at a average price. This restaurant serves and satisfy the needs of both types of customer. Apart from biriyani they also serve many mughal dishes and tandoori items . 
  This restaurant serves biriyani both chicken and mutton biriyani and they provide a 150 gram of chicken or mutton pieces along with their biriyani . They also serve a combo which contains ( chicken biryani 1 plate + 2 pieces kabab + chicken kasha 2 pieces) , in this chicken biriyani they provide normal chicken piece in biriyani and the price of this amazing combo according to their quality food is just cheapest. They serve this combo at just 130 INR. 
  I visited this place few days back and they suggested me try their mutton biriyani where they serve 150 gram rewazi piece mutton @200 per plate. The biriyani was first of all very tasty. The taste was saying that the spices or the quality of raw materials used was of high quality and the mutton and aloo both were very soft and meat was very fresh. I also tried their chicken  tandoori which was also perfect and soft. I would definitely recommend to try their combo and their biriyani which is their speciality.

Chicken shawarma is one of my absolute favourite street foods. You may or not be familiar with it, so hereâ€™s a simple way to make this appetising dish at your homeâ¤ï¸ 

INGREDIENTS
FOR THE CHICKEN
1/2 extra-virgin olive oil
Juice of 1 lemon
3 cloves garlic, minced
2 tsp.salt
1/2 tsp. freshly ground black pepper
1/2 tsp. ground turmeric
1/4 tsp. ground cinnamon
2 lb. boneless skinless chicken thighs
Falafel hot sauce

Ingredients
3/4 cup tomato paste
1/4 cup water
1/2 teaspoon hot sauce
2 cloves garlic (pressed)
1 teaspoon lemon juice
1 tablespoon fresh parsley (finely chopped)
Directions 

In a medium saucepan, combine all ingredients.

Bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low and allow to simmer for 15 to 20 minutes. Stir frequently.

For shawarma sauce  just mix unsweetened yogurt, a bit of lemon juice, garlic, and salt and pepper.

FOR SERVING
Pitas, warmed
Pickled carrots, green chillies, beetroot 
tomatoes, thinly sliced
Cucumber, thinly sliced
Julienne cut cabbage
METHOD

Make chicken: In a large bowl, whisk together oil, lemon juice, garlic, and seasonings. Add chicken and toss to coat. Cover and refrigerate for at least 2 hours and up to overnight. 
Remove chicken and onion from marinade and fry it until chicken is golden and cooked through. 
Let chicken rest on cutting board for 5 minutes, then thinly slice. 
Meanwhile, make shawarma sauce: In a small bowl, whisk together yogurt, lemon juice, oil, and garlic. Season with salt and a pinch of red pepper flakes. To serve as a pita, top warmed pitas with chicken, onion,pickled carrots,chillies and beetroot, tomatoes, cucumber, shawarma sauce  and falafel hot sauce.

âœ¨ SPICED BAKED FRUIT RECIPE âœ¨

Ingredients: 
3 x Pink Lady Apples 
3 x Conference Pears (Medium) 
1 x Punnet Raspberries 
1 x Tin of Peaches in Juice 
4 x Tbsp Coconut Oil (Melted) 
3 x Tbsp Honey or Agave Nectar 
1 x tsp Cinnamon 
1 x tsp Nutmeg 
1 x tsp Ginger 

Make me ğŸ‘‡
Pre-heat oven to 160 degrees Celsius. 

Slice both apples & pears and place into a large mixing bowl. Drain the peach juice into a separate bowl, keep for later, and add to the apples & pears. Combine peach juice with melted coconut oil, honey, cinnamon, nutmeg & ginger. Pour over fruit & throughly coat. 

Evenly place all raspberries in a large baking dish and pour fruit mixture over the top evenly spreading across dish surface. 

Bake in the oven for 60mins, stirring at approximately 30 mins. Serve with a spoonful of coconut yoghurt for a really awesome dessert. 

Nutritional Information 
380 calories per serving (recipe makes 4 servings) 
64.2g Carbs 
14.2g Fat 
2.4g Protein

Did you pick yourself apart?

â€˜OMG I look fatâ€™

â€˜I need to lose weightâ€™
â€˜Diet starts tomorrowâ€™
â€˜I feel embarrassed and ashamed of myselfâ€™

Iâ€™m pretty sure you will have said one or all of these?

How you speak to yourself is huge when it comes to emotional eating.

The more you speak to yourself in a negative way the more you create negative emotions like stress, anxiety, low self esteem, low confidence, low self worth which then creates a physical response.

We then reach out to all the things that make us first better momentarily. Things like food, sex, drugs, alcohol, shopping, gambling, social media, all the things gives us short term pleasure but quite often makes us feel really shit afterwards.

Next time you walk past a mirror listen to your thoughts, they impact everything.

Everything starts with a thought.

Baingan ka bhartağŸŒ¸

Baingan bharta is a spiced and mashed eggplant dish popular in the Indian cuisine
.Baingan (eggplant) is studded with garlic and green chilli roasted on an open flame, and then stir-fried with aromatics for the most delicious smoky flavor. This baingan bharta recipe is a simple and easy to prepare recipe without the use of many spices. This recipe is going to be a sure shot hit at homeâ¤ï¸

INGREDIENTSğŸ‘‡
ğŸ”¸Eggplant/brinjal/baingan-1 (250 gram)
ğŸ”¸Onion 2 medium (sliced)
ğŸ”¸Tomato-1 large (sliced)
ğŸ”¸Garlic cloves 2
ğŸ”¸Green chilli 2 whole
ğŸ”¸Ginger garlic paste 1 tsp
ğŸ”¸Coriander leaves 1/3 cup
ğŸ”¸Cumin seeds 1/2 tsp
ğŸ”¸Green chilli 2 (chopped)
ğŸ”¸Turmeric powder 1/2 tsp
ğŸ”¸Red chilli powder 1/2 tsp
ğŸ”¸Cumin powder 1/2 tsp
ğŸ”¸Coriander powder 1/2 tsp
ğŸ”¸Garam masala powder 1/2 tsp
ğŸ”¸Salt to taste

INSTRUCTIONSğŸ‘‡
Make 2-3 cuts to the brinjal, insertÂ 1-2 green chilli and garlic inside the brinjal.
Turn on the flame and put the brinjal on the gas stove and roast it on medium flame.Flip it and roast it till it is cooked properly from all the sides.
Once the brinjal is roasted properly, turn off the flame and let it cool down completely.Remove the stem and peel it off properly, mash it along with roasted green chilli and garlic.Heat a pan, add oil and let it heat properly.Add cumin seeds,fry it for few seconds on medium flame.Put onion and fry it for 2 mins on medium flame until light brown
Add ginger garlic paste and chopped green chilli, mix it and fry it for 1 minute on medium flame.Reduce the flame to low, add turmeric powder,Â red chilli powder,Â cumin powder and coriander powder.Mix it and cook it for 1 mins on low flame.Add tomato, mix it and fry it for 5 mins on low-medium flame until tomato becomes soft.Add mashed brinjal, salt,Â garam masala powder and coriander leaves, mix it properly.Increase the flame to medium and fry it for a minute, keep stirring.Now low the heat and cook for 3 to 4 mins.Turn off the flame, baingan bharta is ready to serve.Garnish with few coriander leaves.

ğŸ”¸Your delicious Baingan ka bharta  is ready.Serve it with roti,Paratha or riceâ¤ï¸

A BIT ABOUT OJAS ~

Ojas is the essential energy reserve of the body. It literally means â€œvigorâ€. It is the subtle essence of the reproductive fluid and all the vital secretions. It is a special Ayurvedic concept of a source fluid that underlies all our psychoâ€‘physical capacities.
Â 
Ojas is not a physical substance. It is the sap of our life energy and exists on a subtle level in the heart chakra. When it is sufficient, there is health. When it is deficient, there is disease. Disease strikes at the locations where it is weak. In modern terms, we could say that it is something like the essential energy of the immune system. Ojas is defined as:
Â 
* The ultimate essence of the reproductive fluids and the heat of the tissues. Located in the heart, it pervades the entire body, giving stability and support. It is moist, of the nature of nectar (Soma), transparent, a little red and yellow. When it is destroyed, one dies; when it is sustained, one lives.
* Ojas is decreased by such factors as anger, hunger, worry, sorrow and overwork. Then one experiences fear, lack of strength, and constant worry, with disturbed senses. Lacking in lustre, weak in mind, one wastes away. Such qualities as patience and faith disappear

Other factors that decrease Ojas include excessive or unnatural sexual activity and the use of drugs or stimulants, as well as stress, anxiety, devitalized food, pollution, unnatural environment and unrighteous lifestyle. Ever since The Salty Donut expanded into the Orlando area, Iâ€™ve been so excited to check them out. I waited until the lines got shorter (since they were around the blockğŸ˜…) Talk about incredibly fresh and delicious donuts!
ğŸ©
To start, I loved my iced vanilla latte with oat milk. Their house made vanilla syrup is so tasty! ğŸ˜ I ordered 6 donuts, including Mini Rocky Road (brioche filled with marshmallow fluff, chocolate glaze), Butterbeer (butterbeer custard, carmelia glaze, butterscotch drizzle, cookie crumbs, bubble sugar), Maple Bacon (maple glaze, candied bacon, Ivanhoe brewing porter drizzle), Guava (guava, cream cheese glaze, paste Lito puff pastry), Glazed (vanilla bean glaze), Baked Coconut Macaroon (coconut cake, vanilla bean glaze, coconut filling, dark choc), Toasted Coquito (soaked in coquito, chocolate bottom, cinnamon meringue).
ğŸ©
The brioche dough that they use is incredibly soft and fluffy! I love how each donut had a unique flavor combination. You can tell they are all made fresh. My favorites were Toasted Coquito, Butterbeer, and Maple BaconğŸ™Œ Iâ€™d easily give them a 10/10.
ğŸ©
The meringue on the Coquito donut was sooo tasty. The bacon on the Maple Bacon was crispy and added a nice smoky flavor. (I hate bacon donuts that have the pathetic crumblesğŸ˜…) Lastly, there are no words for the Butterbeer donutğŸ¥° It took me back to walking around The Wizarding World of Harry Potter at Universal! Such a delicious flavor and beautiful presentation with the bubble sugar.
ğŸ©
It was well worth the wait. I had been following their Instagram for so long and thought Iâ€™d have to take a drive to Miami to try themğŸ˜ They are located in the Mills area, down the street from East End Market. Everyone in the Orlando area needs to try them!

Ingredients (makes 6):â£â£

â–ªï¸ 2 ripe bananas, mashed
â–ªï¸ 100g self raising flour (I use gluten-free)
â–ªï¸ 1 tsp baking powder
â–ªï¸ 1 tsp cinnamon
â–ªï¸ 1 tbsp maple syrup
â–ªï¸ 140-150ml milk of choice (I use almond)
â–ªï¸ handful chocolate (40-50g), chopped (optional)
â–ªï¸ Coconut oil for frying

1ï¸âƒ£ Peel and add your bananas to a mixing bowl and mash with a fork
2ï¸âƒ£ Now add the flour + baking powder + cinnamon + maple syrup + milk and mix now add the chocolate and mix again
3ï¸âƒ£ Now heat a non stick frying pan with coconut oil and pour in some of the mix. Fry on either side until golden (couple minutes each side)
4ï¸âƒ£ Finally top with whatever you want and serve

FAQ's:â£â£

â¡ï¸ Not gluten-free? Just using standard self raising flour
â¡ï¸ Don't have self raising flour? Use plain flour and add another tsp baking powder

â¡ï¸ Can I use different sweetener? You could use honey, agave or any liquid sweetener. Or if you only have sugar just add 1 tbsp and add a little more milk
â¡ï¸ How to make them banana free? Try using apple sauce instead

Quick crab recipe for you guys! Santa Barbara Sheep Crab, in the family of the Spider Crab, a delicious sweet meat that is light, flavorful, and refreshing! I caught this one with @bmarsh108 recently and made a delicious little meal out of it. Here is the recipe I did:

1. Source a fresh local crab, make sure itâ€™s alive before you prepare it.
2. Sit in 3.5% salt/ice/water solution to stun it and put in the freezer for extra stunning before boiling. 
3. Boil with paprika, bay leaves, and peppercorns for about 15 minutes. Generally when it turns red and starts floating itâ€™s ready.
3. Let cool and then take apart body; crab tools are very useful in this, but you can get creative. Separate the legs and claws from the body, split and remove meat. Separate main body from top shell, cut in half longways and scrape meat from joints and body. 
4. Clean top shell and use as serving dish, place meat in shell. Mix with avocado, lime juice, olive oil, sea salt, and cracked pink peppercorns. Enjoy! ğŸ¦€

One year Meat-freeâ¤ï¸ğŸ§¡ğŸ’›ğŸ’šğŸ’™ğŸ’œ

I was the person who used to make fun of vegetarians. To me, chicken was a vegetable!

My family tells stories of how the first solid food I ever ate was a juicy piece of mutton. And I didn't stop there! 

Growing up, I was pretty indifferent towards animals.  And then April 2009 EVERYTHING changed! My baby girl Sparkle came hopping into my life. She had the key to locks in my heart and soul that I didn't know existed.

From that point on I called myself an "Animal lover". I preferred animals especially dogs over humans. Instead of going out, all I wanted to do was stay at home with my pets babies. (something that holds true to this day).

I started caring deeply for animals &worked towards their welfare. I felt so proud of myself!

And then in Feb 2020 I stumbled upon a term called SPECIESISM. And the deeper I went into the rabbit hole of information (pun intended), I realized I was guilty of it. As someone who from a very young age understood and was against all kinds of 'isms', this was a giant slap in the face.

I realized that I was the person who was using one hand to love a cat or dog, &using the other to pay a butcher. I felt sick!!!

It was like a switch went off in my brain & body. And to set it in stone, a stray dog I used to care for, Pixie, passed away the next day. Seeing the life leave her eyes is a moment I will never forget.
Later I kept thinking that here I am crying for one life, and I actually pay money to murder another for nothing but my pleasure.
That was it for me! 

I used to believe my body NEEDED meat. Oh, how wrong was I! 

Yes there are times I seriously miss it but I think of the bigger picture and get over it. It's tough but worth it! 
No shame to those who continue eating meat. But for the first time in my life I am finally living guilt-free and I seriously couldn't be happier!

I now truly FEEL like an Animal lover ğŸ¤
.

Per il @lunedicucinando di questa settimana l'ospite @lericettedivalentina aveva richiesto una pietanza fritta (o in modo tradizionale o con la friggitrice ad aria). Non avendo la friggitrice ad aria e non essendo io una grande fan del fritto per molti motivi, avevo quasi rinunciato a partecipare.

L'altra sera volevo fare le polpette ma (stranamente!) non volevo farle al forno come al solito.
Mi sono ricordata di un consiglio che mi era stato dato, ovvero di provare a Friggere con l'olio di cocco. Mi ero giÃ  rassegnata ad avere la casa puzzolente per 3 giorni e ad avere problemi di stomaco nelle ore successive.

Invece ne sono rimasta stupita: le polpette erano perfettamente dorate, poco unte, la casa non puzzava minimamente e soprattutto le abbiamo digerite perfettamente! ğŸ˜‰

Ecco quindi le mie polpette fritte in olio di cocco.
Per la foto ho usato la mia nuova tovaglietta ikea (che adoro!) e le mie nuove piantine grasse, che sicuramente non farÃ² morire (sono finte! ğŸ˜‰) ğŸ˜œ

ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§ Good morning guys,

Today's main topic of #lunedicucinandocon is fried food (either traditional or fake with the help of the air fryer). Since I don't own any air fryer and I am not much a fan of fried food for many reasons, I was about not to take part in the initiative this Monday.

The other night I wanted to cook meatballs for dinner but unlikely I didn't want to roast them in the oven as usual.
Then I remembered that a friend once suggested me to try frying in coconut oil. I was consciously aware of the issues I would have dealt with later, like a stinky house for days and stomach pains.

I was positively surprised because my meatballs got amazingly gold brown, they were very less oily, my house didn't stink at all and most of all we didn't faced any stomach pains! ğŸ˜‰

Here are my meatballs fried in coconut oil.
For the set I used some of my latest #ikea purchases: my brand new table mat (which I love!) and and my beloved succulent plants, which won't die for sure (they are fake! ğŸ˜‰) ğŸ˜œ

There's a special polymer in the cell walls of mushrooms that ensure a tender taste, over cooking makes them soggy and lose nutrients too. In fact any food should not be over cooked, this is particularly true of vegetables. 

Many vitamins are sensitive to heat, the amount to vitamin depletes with long cooking. Metabolising food also becomes more difficult once it has been cooked above a certain temperature. 

So be careful next time, always check the cooking time required for cooking that particular veggie or meat!

This is what Black Market by @rangersvalley chuck tail flap looks like when it has been wet aged for 82 days, sliced and set in the fridge overnight. 

Why do you wet age beef, you ask? Because it makes it damn delicious, thatâ€™s why!

Understanding the process and benefits of wet aging is undeniably invaluable. One of lifeâ€™s lessons says hello, yet again - patience. The wet ageing process not only makes the meat significantly more tender, it enhances the flavour and adds a next level depth of beefiness like you wouldnâ€™t believe.

If you were to eat this cut fresh and without any age, you would succumb to a tough and chewy steak. If you understand your meat, your $$$ will go much further. When has unlocking hidden potential ever not been satisfying, anyway?

Time + patience + understanding + amazing produce = unmistakable deliciousness.

Welcome this brand new month with a stunning recipe to make in the comfort of your own home. Youâ€™re going to love it!

Ingredients:
â€¢Chicken thighs
â€¢1 cup of grated Parmesan cheese
â€¢1/2 cup butter (melted)
â€¢1 tsp paprika 
â€¢1 tsp thyme
â€¢1 tsp garlic powder
â€¢Salt and pepper to taste

Directions: 
1.Preheat the oven and grease a baking dish. 
2.In a large bowl, mix the cheese, thyme, paprika, garlic powder, salt and pepper. 
3.Soak the chicken in the melted butter and dip in the mixture. Make sure it is evenly covered. 
4.Add the chicken to the baking dish (skin side up). 
5.Bake for 35-45 minutes. 
6.Serve with vegetables of your choice.

Get your taste buds all fired up with this amazing recipe! Itâ€™s sure to get the new month started on a great note. 

Ingredients: 
â€¢Chicken breasts (skinless and boneless)
â€¢1 tsp garlic powder
â€¢2 tsp oregano
â€¢Salt and pepper to taste
â€¢Fresh parsley

For the sauce:
â€¢Oil
â€¢3 garlic cloves (minced)
â€¢1 cup heavy/whipping cream
â€¢Drizzle of lemon juice
â€¢1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese 
â€¢2-3 cups of asparagus (chopped)
â€¢Cooked pasta (linguine or any pasta of your choice)
â€¢Salt and pepper to taste

Directions: 
1.Flatten the chicken breasts with a rolling pin. 
2.Season the chicken with salt, pepper, garlic powder, oregano, olive oil. 
3.In a large pan, cook the chicken for 5 minutes until golden, remove and set aside. 
4.Add olive oil and minced garlic to the pan and cook for a few seconds. Add the heavy cream and drizzle of lemon juice and allow to simmer. 
5.Add the chopped asparagus to the same pan and cook for 4-5 minutes. 
6.Add the grated cheese and season according to your taste. Cut the chicken into thin strips and add it to the sauce. 
7.Add the cooked pasta and serve with fresh parsley for garnish.

New month, new recipe! Nothing says refreshing quite like this delicious recipe. Enjoy making it as a lovely weekend meal. 

Ingredients:
â€¢1 cucumber
â€¢2 lemons
â€¢1-2 tsp caster sugar 
â€¢1-2 tsp cumin seeds
â€¢2 tsp paprika
â€¢1-2 tsp harissa (chilli pepper paste)
â€¢Fresh coriander
â€¢Salt and pepper to taste
â€¢Cooked rice to serve

Directions:
1.Cut the chicken into cubes and season with salt, pepper and paprika. 
2.Add oil to a heated pan and toss in the cumin seeds. Cook until lightly toasted. 
3.Add the chicken into the pan and cook for 4-5 minutes at high heat. 
4.Add the harissa and chopped coriander to the pan.
5.To make the salad, cut the cucumber in half, lengthways, remove the seeds and cut into slices
6.Pour the squeezed lemon juice into a bowl and add cucumber, caster sugar and a drizzle of oil. Stir thoroughly and place in the refrigerator. 
7.Serve chicken with cooked rice and cucumber salad.

Pork Belly Burnt Ends ğŸ¤¤

Ingredients:
-2-3lbs pork belly slab
-SPG (salt, pepper and garlic powder)
-@spiceology @overthefirecooking Nashville Hot Chicken and Maple Bourbon Seasonings
-1/2 cup of brown sugar
-1/2 cup of butter cut into 8 pieces
- 1 cup of white rice
-1 green onion chopped

Recipe-
-Cook your rice ahead of time. And if you donâ€™t know how to cook rice get a ride cookerğŸ˜‚
-Rub whole pork belly with SPG and keep covered in the fridge overnight. 
-Wash remaining season off of pork belly with water and then pat dry.
-Cut pork belly into 1-2 in. cubes and cover in your favorite seasoning.
-Smoke at 250F. For 2.5 hours in a rimmed tray. (Make sure you have a rimmed tray as the pork will render a lot of fat)
-Donâ€™t look until that 2.5 hours is up ğŸ¤¥
-Add butter and brown sugar and mix.
-Smoke for an additional 1.5 hours 
-Toss the Pork Belly in the remaining juices and serve immediately with white rice and chopped green onions. 

Enjoy!!ğŸ˜‹

Variety is the spice of life right?  Well our cats agree and as most of you know we raw feed here.  While we grind our own blend some families cannot and still want to continue with the healthiest diet for their kitties...which is raw.  We have always recommended the best and most convenient by having delicious balanced meat blends delivered right to your door from @darwinspetfood.
Here you see Zaia, Zilly and Gia getting to choose from chicken, lamb and turkey.  Itâ€™s funny because they definitely let you know what they like best and when they want something different.  Itâ€™s normal for cats to want you to rotate their proteins and Darwins makes that easy.

While we know that many people feed raw there are some that are new to the concept so we are happy to answer questions if you have them. But basically...

ğŸ† Cats (all cats) are obligate carnivores.  So itâ€™s a species appropriate diet for them just like veggies are species appropriate to a rabbit.

ğŸ† Taurine is so important to the diet of your cat for their own organs especially the â¤ï¸ and that is found in organ meats and dark meats so making sure your raw blend is balanced is SOOO important.

ğŸ† Moisture is essential in a cats diet and raw provides that while dry foods can dehydrate them and lead to kidney issues long term.

If you have questions or would like to try out some raw blends for your  kitty we are here for you and so is Darwins. Right now you can place an order @darwinspetfood and use coupon code leapoffaith for additional savings.

Beans stew is one of the famous Lebanese everyday comfort dishes. People either love it or hate it; no middle ground.
.

Normally cooked with meat cubes (I use beef shanks), yet some chooose to go totally vegan. Served with vermicelli rice, and an extra squeeze of lemon juice. My daughters however opt for a generous drizzle of pomegranate molasses. This is an essential dish on our menu. We make it frequently, especially that I always have the beans ready in the freezer. I usually get the beans (huge amounts!) when they are in season, boil them a bit & freeze them for quick use.
.

What is your favourite Lebanese stew?

==================================

On Saturday I made breakfast tacos, on Sunday I air-fried them into chimichangas. 

Creating and experimenting with new recipes is fun and a cool creative outlet. It reminds me of childhood creation without fear of failure - the worst case scenario is I still get to eat meat. 

So much of my life is focused on production and output. And donâ€™t get me wrong, I love the simplicity of putting in the work I know will get me the results I want. I do think my life is better when I make time to play and to create, to be inspired and inspire others in return 

My goal is to keep playing, to keep discovering, and to keep enjoying my life and the food that I eat. 

Who wants to play with me?

A strong, sturdy, ğŸ’ª high quality design of the Granola Bar Pan definitely outperforms the others!!! â 
â 
When buying silicone bakeware you want to look for these things:â 
â 
- 100% food grade silicone, at least FDA approved but LFGB approved is even better!!!â 
â 
- Sturdy design so the pan won't spill when moving the filled pan.â 
â 
- No added fillers, especially plastic (BPA etc.) If you know the company or they have a good reputation it's likely that if they advertise "no fillers" then there are none.â 
â 
- Pinch test to see if silicone MIGHT have fillers (this test isn't always accurate but might be helpful) 1. fold silicone 2. twist the folded edge 3. if the silicone shows white then it could have fillers.â 
â 
- How does the bakeware smell? It should not smell like chemicals!!!â 
.â 
.â 
.â

lately always wondering why I don't fit in with others, or why it's hard to like be interesting enough in the midst of conversation; essentially trying to hard to be liked amongst friends--

for the longest time I've often wondered is there something wrong with me; & now I just really don't care...

I'd rather be weird quirky Gabby who's into yoga, old movies ,books, music & anime, vintage/edgy/hippie shit; than someone who's into what's cool or popular in the now. waste is a concept that humankind has created.

itâ€™s programmed in our minds from the day that weâ€™re bornâ€¦once something is damaged, we throw it away. once something is no longer useful to us personally, we throw it away. once something is coming of age, we throw it away for something thatâ€™s shiny and new.

and although it can be so easy to throw the blame at the productâ€”to yell from rooftops that plastic is the devilâ€”the truth is that our landfills arenâ€™t overflowing because of the types of product we put in them; itâ€™s because of the rate at which we produce, consume, generate and DISPOSE of it.

for example, plastic is a material that has made our modern life possible; it makes our vehicles lighter resulting in fewer carbon emissions. it has transformed modern-day medicine. it is essential for those in the disabled community. it has given clean drinking water to those who desperately need it.

what weâ€™re trying to say is that the problem isnâ€™t plastic; itâ€™s our mindset as a society. disposable is convenient, reusable is a hassle.

we are currently in a society where convenience, cost, and accessibility is more important than the health of the planet thatâ€™s keeping us afloat. fortunately, making changes isnâ€™t always complicated. most of the time, itâ€™s about breaking habits.

>> what do we do with our kitchen waste?

>> do we use worn-out clothes as rags?

>> where do our glass alcohol bottles go?

>> can we create face scrubs with waste fruit peels?

>> can we upcycle cardboard boxes and tissue paper rolls?

go on. ask yourself.
.
.

All lives matter, from these tiny ants to the enormous elephants. It disappoints me to see non-human animals suffer due to our ignorance, carelessness and lack of awareness. 

Non-human animals feel all emotions that we humans feel. It would be selfish for us to disregard them and their feelings. Selfishness is when we put our wants before otherâ€™s needs and this is the case when we choose to eat animals for our pleasure or habit. And here is the truth: we donâ€™t need to eat animals for our survival; itâ€™s simply a subconscious want. But for the other, itâ€™s a need for them to survive/live. 

Letâ€™sâ€¦
â€¢	Check under our parked vehicle before we start the engine and drive off.
â€¢	Drive slow while being conscious of other beings.
â€¢	Not disturb any habitat: from a single tree to a large forest with wildlife, from a single nest to the skies that the birds fly or from a pond to the vast ocean where the fish swim.
â€¢	Make sure there are no ants or insects on the table top before we place any hot object (such as tray just off the oven) on the table.
â€¢	Not use fire crackers that give off loud sounds and pollute the air.
â€¢	Wash our dishes as soon as we eat so that we donâ€™t have to feel frustrated about waiting till the ants leave or even carelessly wash them away.
â€¢	Not use harmful chemicals to kill insects.
â€¢	Not use animals for entertainment purposes like circus and perahara.
â€¢	Not ride on animals.
â€¢	Not train dogs in harsh manner and use them as our guards or for investigation purposes.
â€¢	Choose to live a vegan lifestyle: use animal-friendly material and eat vegan meals.

These ants matter regardless of their size. We refer to them as tiny relative to us. No matter their size, appearance, age or species, their life matters.

Kavindi Bandara - Project Manager, Selyn Foundation

"I have started my career as an HR professional. Joining Selyn was the turning point of my career. At Selyn, I learned about the Fair Trade concept and put it in to practice sustainably. Fairtrade is a wonderful guideline, which enables you to do good for people and the planet.

When our chairman, Mrs Sandra Wandurangala, was planning to launch the Reusable Fabric Sanitary Napkins as a passion project, I happily engaged with the initiative since I am a zero-waste practitioner. We launched this project with the concept of 'Buy One - Gift One' campaign. Once a customer purchases a Selyn reusable sanitary napkin, we match and donate a napkin to a woman in need in vulnerable communities. Not only we are providing a sustainable solution to one-time-use sanitary pads, but we are also empowering the women in rural areas to face the period days with comfort and dignity. In a society where menstruating is looked as something to be ashamed of, I am extremely grateful to be involved in a project to help women overcome barriers. With Selyn, I can impact someone's life positively."

Selyn is joining hands with @wfto_fairtrade and women worldwide to celebrate women's achievements, raise awareness against bias and take action for equality. Follow us and stay tuned to learn more about how #WomenOfFairTrade from the small island of Sri Lanka #ChooseToChallege inequality, take a stand and set an example. #AllForFairTrade

Vegan Pizza Recipe

The only thing better than Pizza, is Vegan Pizza!

Preparation time: 2 hours

Difficulty: Medium 

Ingredients:
â€“ 100grs of Adaâ€™s Vegan Brie
â€“ 1/2 cup of hot Water
- 1 cup lukewarm water
- 1 tablespoon yeast 
- 1.5 tablespoon sugar 
- 2.5 cups of flour
- 1/8 cup of olive oil
â€“ 1 small diced Onion
â€“ Tomato Paste
â€“ Dried Rosemary, Basil, Marjoram, Thyme, Oregano.
â€“ Green Basil
â€“ Green Pepper
â€“ Mushrooms
â€“ Black Olives
â€“ Salt

Recipes:
1- Mix half a cup of lukewarm water with sugar & yeast, wait 10 mins for the yeast to foam & double in size.
2- Add salt & 1 cup of flour.
3- While mixing, add the olive oil, water & flour.
4- Knead the dough with your hands, shape it like a ball and place it in a bowl with a towel covering it to rest and rise.
5- In a bowl, mix Adaâ€™s Vegan Brie with warm water and whisk till you have a smooth cheese mixture.
6- Add a pinch of salt to it.
7- In a pan, sauteÌ the onions with olive oil.
8- Add in the tomato paste diluted in a bit of water, salt, dried basil, rosemary, marjoram, thyme & oregano.
9- Slice the mushrooms, olives & green pepper.
10-By now, the doughâ€™s size  has doubled, kneed it again, & cover with towel for 30 more minutes then roll the dough on a floured surface to form a circle.
11- Place the dough on parchment paper & bake it for about 10 mins.
12- Bring the dough out of the oven, spread the tomato sauce all over the dough, then place the mushrooms & green pepper.
13- With a spoon spread the Vegan Brie mixture you made on top of the dough, then add the olives.
14- Bake Pizza for 15 mins.
15- Add some shredded green basil on top.
16- Cut & Serve.

You can use Adaâ€™s Vegan Mozzarella or Adaâ€™s Vegan Cheddar instead of Adaâ€™s Vegan Brie...
We used the basic veggies, but you can use any vegetable you like as toppings for your Pizza...

 ğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡

 You need :

 3 cups of oatmeal
 1.5 cups of peanut butter (crunchy for me)
 1/2 cup honey / maple syrup
 1/3 cup coconut oil
 1 tsp vanilla
 1/2 tsp salt
 1 cup of dark chocolate chips + 2 tbsp of coconut oil

 What you should do:

 In a food processor, crush the oats then incorporate the rest of the ingredients (except the chocolate and the 2 tbsp of coconut oil)

 Place this mixture in a pyrex with a sheet of parchment.  Squeeze the mixture well.

 Place in the fridge.  Meanwhile, melt the chocolate and coconut oil in the microwave, mix every 30 sec.

 Pour the chocolate over the oat mixture and put it in the fridge again, until it is firm, then cut into pieces!

EASY LASAGNA VEGAN RICOTTA ROLL UPS!  By @alexafuelednaturally 
10 ounce bag frozen spinach (optional)
Lasagna noodles (I used jovial GF ones) 
2 tbsp olive oil 
32 ounces marinara sauce (my favorites are @raoshomemade or @otamotfoods) 
1 (14 ounces) container firm tofu
Juice of 1 lemon
1/2 tsp salt
4 tbsp nutritional yeast
1/2 tsp garlic powder
Fresh basil to garnish
.
Instructions: 
1. Preheat oven to 350. Then cook your lasagna noodles! Undercook by 2 minutes. 
2. Remove tofu from package and wrap tofu block in 2 paper towels. Squeeze for 10 seconds then break apart tofu into your food processor. To the food processor add salt, 2 tbsp olive oil, lemon juice, nutritional yeast and garlic powder. Pulse 6-10 times until you reach the consistency of ricotta cheese. Taste and adjust salt and seasonings as needed.
3. In a pan add frozen spinach and season with a small pinch of salt and pepper. Cook for 2-3 minutes m. Remove from pan and add to ricotta. I pulsed 3-4 times into the ricotta.
4. Spread marinara sauce sauce onto the bottom of a oven-proof skillet; set aside. (I use a cast iron) 
5,Once lasagna noodles are cooked, drain then immediately drizzle with olive oil so they donâ€™t stick together. Grab a lasagna noodles and Spread a couple spoonfuls  ricotta mixture evenly along leaving the last inch bare. Roll up and place in the prepared skillet; repeat with remaining pasta noodles and filling.
5. Place into oven and bake for 10 minutes. 
6. Serve immediately. Garnish with ground pepper and fresh basil, chili pepper flakes & an optional drizzle of olive oil. â€¢â€¢

Gnocchi with Veggies in Creamy Sauce 

I love this delicious nondairy cream sauce. It's so rich and creamy, you'd never know it was dairy-free! ğŸ˜‰

Recipe:
ğŸ¥Ÿ 16oz package potato gnocchi
ğŸŒ° 1 clove garlic, minced or pressed
ğŸ¥’ 1 medium zucchini, cut into half moons
ğŸ… 8oz grape tomatoes, cut in half lengthwise 
ğŸ¥¬ 3 cups spinach leaves
ğŸ§€ 1 Tbsp vegan butter (I prefer @earthbalance buttery spread with olive oil) 
ğŸ² 1/2 cup vegetable stock
ğŸ§€ 4oz vegan cream cheese (I used @kitehillfoods almond milk cream cheese)
ğŸ§‚ Salt and freshly ground black pepper

1. Cook gnocchi according to package directions. Drain, cover, and set aside, reserving 1/2 cup pasta water.
2. Meanwhile, melt butter in a large saute pan over medium heat.
3. Add garlic and zucchini to pan with melted butter. Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Saute until zucchini begins to soften, about 5 minutes. 
4. Add vegetable stock and cream cheese to pan with zucchini. Heat until cream cheese is melted, stirring occasionally. 
5. Add tomatoes and spinach to pan with sauce. Stir until spinach is wilted and tomatoes begin to soften. 
6. Add gnocchi to pan with sauce and veggies. Stir to coat, adding a small amount of reserved pasta water to thin the sauce if needed. 
7. Season with pepper, serve, and enjoy!

ğŸŒ± How to start eating more whole food plant-based ğŸŒ±

After I made the post about being mostly whole food plant-based (WFPB), I received some questions from people whoâ€™d like to know how they can start doing that, too. I think itâ€™s worth noting that when I started eating WFPB, it was already 11 years since I went vegetarian and 8 years since I went vegan. So for me, it was really about cutting out processed plant foods rather than cutting out any animal products. Here are some of the tips that have helped me:
1ï¸âƒ£ Replace oil with water or vegetable broth when cooking.
2ï¸âƒ£ Replace salt with miso, or if you have access, try salt substitute â€œTable Tasty.â€
3ï¸âƒ£ Replace sugar with date syrup when baking (search â€œdate syrupâ€ on NutritionFacts.org for recipe).
4ï¸âƒ£ Replace refined grains with whole grains such as millets, quinoa, whole wheat noodles, etc.
5ï¸âƒ£ Try not to have processed foods at home at all so you naturally wouldnâ€™t eat them.
6ï¸âƒ£ Try your best when you eat out, and if you really want that vegan chocolate cake topped with cream and packed with sugar...just enjoy it and donâ€™t feel bad (I just had two pieces of an amazing vegan coconut strawberry cake last night). Itâ€™s really the day-to-day stuff you eat that counts.
7ï¸âƒ£ Ask the restaurant to accomodate. For example, one of my favorite restaurants adds rice cakes to their spinach salad dish. I always ask them to take out the rice cakes and give me more spinach instead.
8ï¸âƒ£ Find your favorite organic vegetable supplier and know where your food comes from. Talk to the people who grow your food. It may bring appreciation and make your meal prepping experience nicer, at least for me!
9ï¸âƒ£ For more healthy recipes, check out the How Not to Die Cookbook and follow @nutrition_facts_org for the latest science on evidence-based nutrition.

Who does not love Stuffed Baked Potatoes with Mushroom and Spinach? ğŸ¥”ğŸ„ğŸŒ± Share your thoughts in the comments ğŸ’­ .
ğŸ“¸ by @twospoons.ca
.
So easy and full of flavor! 
Get the recipe:

Recipe: 
4 russet potatoes
1 tbsp coconut oil
2 cloves garlic , finely chopped
4 cups (250g) cremini mushrooms
pinch salt
1 tbsp almond butter
1 tbsp balsamic vinaigrette
1 tbsp lemon juice
4 cups baby spinach (approx. 2 handfuls)
.
.
1. Preheat oven to 425F/215C. Poke holes around each potato using a fork (this will help the heat to escape while baking). Wrap each in tin foil and bake in the oven for 40-50, or until you can easily poke through the cooked potatoes with a toothpick.
2. In a skillet add coconut oil, garlic, sliced mushrooms and pinch salt. Cook on medium heat for 5-10 minutes. 
3. Whisk together almond butter, balsamic and lemon juice and pour over mushrooms. Continue cooking until mushrooms are browned and ready to eat, then toss in baby spinach and cook until wilted (2-3 minutes). Slice open baked potatoes and fill with mushroom and spinach medley. Optional to drizzle with vegan gravy. .

LEFTOVER RICE AND MIX VEGETABLES BALLS
Mixed vegetables Rice Bombs no oil fry 
#vegetables #rice #balls #oil #nobutter #nooilfry  #snack #appetizer #starter 
INGREDIENTS-:
1 -cup  Boiled rice 
1 tbsp finely chopped ya grated cabbage 
1tbsp chopped ya grated carrot 
1 chopped green chilli 
1 tbsp chopped capsicum 
salt according to taste 
1/4 tsp red chilly powder 
2  tsp oil 
1/4  tsp chaat masala 
1 tsp mango powder 
1-1/2  tbsp rice flour 
1 tbsp chopped coriander 
METHOD-:
1- Boiled rice ko grinder me pees le. 
2- Vegetables ko chopper me chopped kar le ya grate kar le.
3- Ek bowl me peesa rice aur vegetables mix kare. 
4- Sabhi dry masala mix kare aur rice flour mix kare. 
5- chopped chilly aur coriander mix kare aut thoda sa oil mix kare.
6- Haath me thoda oil laga kar mixture lekar balls bana le..
7- Appam pan ko oil se brush kare aur balls daal kar slow gas me pakne de phir dusre side palat de .
8- Tomato sauce aur green chilli ke saath serve kare. 
tips -Haath ko rice flour  se ya maida se dust karke bhi balls bana sakte chipkenge nahi.
Agar thoda gilla lag raha to maida ya rice flour mix kar sakte.

Marchâ€¦ Spring. Crisp, sunny mornings. Longer, warmer days. Trees coming into leaf. Flowers starting to blossom. Birds chirping away. Everything feels like it is beginning to come aliveâ€¦ 

This month on the farm, as well as handpicking our study winter crops - cauliflower, leeks, purple sprouting, chard, celeriac and beetroot - we will be starting to see the first of our early baby lettuce, baby spinach and beautiful, tart and tender rhubarb. 

The farm team are also busy preparing the fields for the new season crops to be planted. As we are a traditional, mixed farm we have a circular, self-sufficient farming system. The manure that our native Ruby Red cattle produce in the winter months, is now being spread across our fields, ready to be ploughed in. This provides important natural nutrients and increases the organic matter, improving the soils fertility and overall condition. This helps us grow strong, nutrient dense fruit and vegetables that are full of flavour; along with a healthy crop of luscious rich grass for our cattle to graze in the summer months and cereals to feed on in the winter. 

We are also heading into the season for Spring Lamb, Easter is fast approaching (along with all of the seasonal sweet treats that come with it!) & there are brighter days ahead!

Donâ€™t forget about tomatoes just yet, they are at their best just after a warm summer .... keeping cool with this kind of dip, kind of salad .... Roast Tomatoes &  @thecocotribe Yoghurt with herbie butterbeans ... if there was a dish that summed up our love of the simple things done well with max flavour and goodness, this is it ... dive in and scoop up with crusty bread or serve along side grilled fish, meat or vegetables. Recipe below ... enjoy friends ğŸŒ±ğŸŒ± 

INGREDIENTS

3 vine ripened tomatoes, cut in half
2 tbsp olive oil
Salt, fresh ground black pepper

 

2 cups @thecocotribe Greek style yoghurt
1 clove garlic, crushed
Â¼ cup pitted Kalamata olives, roughly chopped

1 tin butter beans, drained, rinsed
Â¼ cup dairy free pesto
juice of  1 lemon 

1 tbsp zaâ€™atar
1 tbsp pomegranate molasses
Â½ cup mint, picked
2 tbsp olive oil

METHOD 

 Preheat oven to 180C and line a baking tray with baking paper. 

Lay the tomatoes cut side up on the lined tray, drizzle with the olive oil and season lightly with salt and pepper. Roast for approx. 50 minutes until they have softened and become slightly wrinkly.

Allow to cool, then roughly chop tomatoes, reserve Â¼ of the tomato  and stir the rest into the yoghurt, along with the garlic, olives and a light seasoning. Refrigerate for at least 30 minutes. 

In a mixing bowl, combine the butterbeans, pesto, reserved tomato, lemon and a little salt and pepper. 

 Spoon this butterbean salad over the yoghurt, finishing with  zaâ€™atar, molasses, mint and olive oil.

A good salad really makes a meal.

Last night, we had a BBQ and I made this salad to go with it:
.
ğŸ¥— 2 handfuls of rocket leaves 
ğŸ¥— 1 handful of basil leaves
ğŸ¥— 2 medium zucchini, sliced into 1 rounds and grilled
ğŸ¥— 4-6 small tomatoes or 1 punnet of cherry tomatoes, sliced
ğŸ¥— 2 tbs feta, crumbled
.
- Place all salad ingredients into a bowl.
- Make dressing by combining 2tbs extra virgin olive oil, 1 tbs white wine vinegar, 1 tsp wholegrain mustard and 1 tsp of honey. Mix well.
- Pour dressing over salad and lightly toss to coat.
.
A great salad for using seasonal vegetables that are available at the shops, or those that are from your garden. All but the rocket was from either my garden or Mum and Dadâ€™s garden!

Until about a year or so ago, whenever I had a day or two off work over a weekend, you would often find me ready with my trolley and a small backpack full of books, ready to leave work a little earlier to go off and catch a flight or a train to somewhere. 

This time round, I didnâ€™t have to pack any basics or books and I canâ€™t even remember where the trolley is. I could however step out of my front door, get on my bicycle (a great birthday present from last year), and explore the countryside nearby here and cherish being in nature, the one thing that keeps me going.

This weekend has featured a trip to my favourite vegetable shed market. Walks in the nearby parks, which I now know by heart. Digging soil in my back garden, to get it ready to welcome the seedlings and small plants Iâ€™m patiently growing inside my living room (orto in the making). Watching daffodils and hyacinths open up under the warmth of the sun. Getting fresh flowers which bring scents and colours in my house. Buying some more houseplants for my urban jungle (I just canâ€™t stop doing this). Chanting and learning Sanskrit, something I started back in December and itâ€™s been one of the most wonderful ways to spend my Sunday mornings so far, waking up early and flowing softly in the beauty of these blissful sounds. Learning all about henna and the Indian beauty rituals. Enjoying a warm latte with a freshly baked bun in the park while looking at the sun reflecting in the water and calming my mind down.

Zucchini slice recipe.. 

If you are looking for a quick and easy high protein snack that is kid friendly... Enter my zucchini slice recipe.. very very interchangeable to suit your families taste preferences.

Great to pre prepare and a wonderful addition to a lunchboxğŸ˜

Recipe makes 12 serves
 
Ingredients: 
- 220g zucchini
- 125g corn
- 75g mushrooms
- 20g spinach
- 40 g onion
- 155 g cottage cheese
- 6 chicken eggs
- 60 g ham
- 40 g wholemeal self raising flour
- salt & pepper
- olive oil spray or olive oil 5g 

Method

- Set oven at 190 degrees 
- Add oil to pan and cook off just to soften vegetables and ham, add salt and pepper to season. 
- Line your tray with foil and spray so slice doesn't stick.
- Whisk eggs and flour 
- Add vegetables and ham to tray.
- Pour egg mixture on top and tap tray on your bench or workspace to ensure egg mixture has covered entire tray to the bottom. 
- Add dollops or cottage cheese on top of egg & vegetables
- Place in oven and bake for 30 minutes or until golden brown.

Nutrition: - per serve 78 cals 
Protein 6.3g, carbohydrates 5.1g Fats 3.4g, fibre 1.2g 

Enjoy ğŸ˜Š

**Notes - you may want to substitute cottage cheese for ricotta and add a little more flour for more height on your slice. (This will change the nutritional value from above. )

captions:
"We're starting off the week and the month with something a little different. A presentation of March #season. Walking into spring, we have a large variety of newcomers.

In the ancient Indian practice of #ayurveda, there is a special term for eating seasonally: #ritucharya. 

The concept of ritucharya breaks down what to eat during each season to maintain health and prevent disease.

Why the Apron Boy promotes seasonal eating:
-Seasonal Products are better for your health, studies show that vegetables able to follow their natural growing and ripening cycles are more nutritious than their fellow brothers due to post-harvest treatments and ripening agents.

-They just taste better- anyone experienced lackluster tomatoes or tasteless strawberries? Need I say more? To take the test I recommend comparing all-year long supermarket products with seasonal #farmersmarket and comment on the difference!

-Better for the environment as they consume less chemical agents and usually incur less transportation

- And Finally, Cheaper, you'd probably pay twice as much for berries in Winter as you would in the Summer!

So What's peak in March?
Beetroot- pairs well with goat cheese , nuts, citrus, vinegar, Apple and Fennel. ideal in soups (like borsh), risotto or smoothies !
Artichoke- pairs well with Parmesan cheese, Thyme, Basil, Lamb, Mushrooms and White wine
White,Red, Chinese Cabbage- Delicious in a slaw, spring rolls or Sauerkraut pairs well with Oranges, Soy Sauce, Ham, and Vinegar
Jerusalem Artichoke-Mashed, Grilled or in a creamy soup it goes in par with grapefruit, hazelnut, Prosciutto and Honey
Radish- Amazing pickled, it goes well with bread, butter or tzatziki
Brussels Sprouts- Grilled or Roasted is the answer

In season also, spring onions, sweet potatoes, cauliflowers and endives, sadly I couldn't get hand on broccoli and parsnips

On the fruit side we have Grapefruit, apples Granny, Golden and Gala, Avocado, Pineapple.
Happy March Season
@yannphotography

ARE YOU MISSING ART?

I am. Badly missing it.

Art is still there, but with galleries and museums shut, itâ€™s a pleasure and joy we have to live without for the time being. 

Or do we? As an artist I make paintings to be seen. It doesnâ€™t seem right that they are shut away.

Thinking about this I came up with a way of getting art to people at a time when people canâ€™t get to see art. 

BRING IT ON HOME

Would it lighten up lockdown to have an original painting in your home?

Just for this one unusual year, I have decided to offer paintings from my studio on temporary, affordable loan to your home. 

Choose a painting youâ€™d like to live with for a while and Iâ€™ll send it to you direct.
 
IFYOU CANâ€™T GO TO THE GALLERY, WHY NOT LET THE GALLERY COME TO YOU? 

I have selected paintings that are a celebration of London and Londoners and the vibrant, multicultural street life that we dearly hope will return soon. Each day Iâ€™ll be posting a painting thatâ€™s available for loan.

Perhaps one of these paintings will spark your imagination and keep alive hopes for the future?

ğŸƒ WHEN NOT TO HAVE PAPAYAS ğŸƒ

Papayas have umpteen benefits but EXTRA care is to be given on when you should AVOID eating papaya all together. 
ğŸƒ Papayas in Pregnancy are a big no no. They cause uterine contractions which can lead to abortion. 
ğŸƒ Papaya intake while pregnancy has been linked to birth defects in babies by many researches.
ğŸƒ Papayas should also be avoided by lactating mothers since it can be toxic to babies and cause some serious illnesses. 
ğŸƒ Having papaya more than 1 cup in a day can damage oesophagus. So have papaya in little quantities.
ğŸƒ Papaya is one of those fruits which can cause allergic reaction to people with sensitive immune system. 
ğŸƒ Papaya brings down blood glucose level; if consumed carelessly, blood glucose levels can drop to dangerous levels.
ğŸƒ Papaya Affects male fertility by decreasing sperm count and mobility. 
ğŸƒ Benzyl isothiocyanate is present in it, so consuming it in large quantity can be toxic. 
ğŸƒ It is highly recommended for couples who are trying to conceive or have conceived to avoid papaya intake. 
Enjoy papaya once in a while keeping in mind the above mentioned guidelines.

MEET RON FINLEY: also known as the Guerrilla Gardner. He is from South Los Angeles, who noticed that his community had little to no access to healthy and nutritious foods without having to go to another neighborhood. Ron disliked that so he took action by planting a garden right outside his home in 2010. The city gave him a citation because the area he grew fruits and vegetables were owned by the city. Soon after, Ron along with his group LA Green Grounds was able to get the law changed so that no one would be fined for growing food on the sidewalk strips. Believe it or not, he does more than what he is talked about for such as one of his careers as a fashion designer and is an owner of many blaxploitation original posters. As a fashion designer he has created pieces for pro-athletes and most recently did a collab with everybody.world clothing as well as his own merch on his website(right now is sold out). As for his infamous urban gardening, he had his own Masterclass just 8 months ago & presently, still grows plants and they are available for sale through the Ron Finley Project.

A complete plate of happiness: Eggplant dish, rice & tahdig (crispy rice). These days more than ever I am mindful of every little peace of food we consume. On a continuous effort to minimize the amount of food waste in our household. We try to ration our meals as to not waste even a single grain of rice! 
I can only imagine how much hard work from farmers and grocery store staff (just to name a few) have gone into a plate full of food that appears on our table in these difficult times. 
Salut to those who work hard these days so that we have good quality food to eat.

It was time for some Mexican style corn with a bit of a Persian touch and fresh lime! Yum!
